	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span><br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I agree with you that there is absolutely no reason to train any in conjuration or evocation; you will use those skills so often that they will always be high.<br><br>Divination and abjuration you won't use as much, but they're important to keep up anyway. Thankfully, if your skill is a little low, you can just cast Sense Summoned or Minor Shielding on yourself while waiting for a boat or whatnot and your skills will raise quite nicely.<br><br>The big bear, though, is alteration. You don't get any alteration spells at all until level 8, I believe, and you won't use that pet heal spell enough to get your skill up very high. You'll use burnout (another alteration skill) pretty frequently after level 12, but that alone isn't going to raise your skill very high either.<br><br>However, at level 24 you get your first Malise spell, which is alteration based and will become a very important spell for you the further you progress through the game, so it's really important to work on alteration at least at this point.<br><br>If you want to be a little thrifty with your practice points, save all you can and put a few into alteration, because it will be the single hardest skill to raise and you will be pretty frustrated at level 24 if your skill is too low.<br><br>But do save up a few skill points for later. You'll be thankful when you use up six Words of Fizzle trying to make your level 39 pets because your research skill is horrible. Just bite the bullet and spend the plat on training so you can put the grimoire back on the bookshelf and go out and kill more stuff. :-)</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
